  "hash": "sha256:a3f1c2e4b7d09e5f1a2b3c4d5e6f7a8b9c0d1e2f3a4b5c6d7e8f9a0b1c2d3e4f",
  "signature": "ed25519:b4e2d1f3c5a7091e2b3c4d5e6f7a8b9c0d1e2f3a4b5c6d7e8f9a0b1c2d3e4f5a",
  "hasCredibilityFactor": [
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Software quality assurance",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Simulation software (Ansys Mechanical 2022 R2) is used under a validated installation with documented version control. SQA procedures comply with FDA 21 CFR Part 11 and internal QMS SOP-SIM-004. Required level 2 demands traceable version records and documented test cases; achieved level 3 additionally includes regression testing across releases.",
      "rationale": "The FEA ensemble employs Ansys Mechanical 2022 R2 under a quality management system that satisfies 21 CFR Part 11 electronic records requirements. Installation qualification (IQ) and operational qualification (OQ) records are archived under document control number QMS-SIM-2022-014. Regression test suite comprising 47 benchmark cases is executed at each software update; all cases pass within specified tolerances. Version control is enforced via Git with signed commits; model files are archived in a validated PLM system. These controls exceed the Gradation 2 threshold and satisfy Gradation 3 criteria."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Code verification requires demonstration that the solver correctly implements the mathematical model for linear and nonlinear structural mechanics. Required level 2 mandates comparison against at least one analytical or manufactured solution for the relevant physics class.",
      "rationale": "Ansys Mechanical has been verified against NAFEMS benchmark set LE1–LE11 covering linear elasticity, and against the method-of-manufactured-solutions (MMS) suite for nonlinear contact. Internal verification report VER-2022-007 documents agreement within 0.3% for linear cases and within 1.1% for nonlinear contact cases, both within the specified tolerance of 2%. This satisfies Gradation 2 requirements."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Discretization error must be quantified via systematic mesh refinement study. Required level 3 demands a formal Richardson extrapolation or grid convergence index (GCI) analysis demonstrating that discretization error contributes less than 5% to the total simulation uncertainty budget.",
      "rationale": "A three-level mesh refinement study was conducted with element edge lengths of 1.0 mm, 0.5 mm, and 0.25 mm in the screw shank and rod regions. Richardson extrapolation yields an asymptotic convergence ratio of 1.94 (theoretical: 2.0 for quadratic elements), confirming the solution is in the asymptotic range. GCI for the finest mesh is 1.8% for stiffness and 2.3% for yield force, both below the 5% threshold. The 0.5 mm mesh was selected for production runs as it achieves GCI < 3% with acceptable computational cost."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Solver error assessment requires documentation of iterative convergence criteria and demonstration that residuals are reduced to levels that do not materially affect QoI predictions. Required level 2 mandates force and displacement residuals below 1e-4 relative norm.",
      "rationale": "Newton-Raphson iterations are converged to a force residual norm of 1e-5 and displacement residual norm of 1e-5, one order of magnitude tighter than the required threshold. Solver settings are documented in simulation setup record SIM-SETUP-COU1-v3. No unconverged load steps were observed across the 11-construct ensemble."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Use error controls require that simulation inputs, boundary conditions, and post-processing steps are reviewed by an independent analyst. Required level 2 mandates a documented peer review of the simulation setup prior to result extraction.",
      "rationale": "All simulation setups were independently reviewed by a second licensed engineer (PE) not involved in model construction. Review checklist SIM-REVIEW-COU1 covers boundary condition assignment, material property mapping, contact definition, and load application. Three minor discrepancies were identified and corrected prior to final runs. Review sign-off is archived in the QMS."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Model form adequacy requires justification of constitutive model selection and contact formulation relative to the physics of interest. Required level 3 demands sensitivity analysis demonstrating that model form choices do not dominate the uncertainty budget.",
      "rationale": "The pedicle screw construct is modeled with isotropic linear elasticity for the titanium alloy (Ti-6Al-4V, E=114 GPa, ν=0.34) and frictional Coulomb contact (μ=0.2) at the screw-rod interface. Sensitivity studies varied the friction coefficient (0.1–0.4) and elastic modulus (±5%) showing less than 3% variation in stiffness and less than 4% variation in yield force. Plasticity was incorporated via a bilinear isotropic hardening model calibrated to tensile coupon data; the model form was validated against published coupon results. These analyses confirm model form uncertainty is not the dominant contributor."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Model input uncertainty must be characterized for all influential parameters identified by sensitivity analysis. Required level 3 demands probabilistic characterization (distribution type and parameters) for the top three sensitivity-ranked inputs.",
      "rationale": "Global sensitivity analysis (Sobol indices, N=1024 quasi-random samples) identified elastic modulus, yield strength, and screw-rod friction coefficient as the three most influential inputs. Material properties were characterized from N=20 tensile coupons (E: mean=114.2 GPa, CV=1.8%; σ_y: mean=910 MPa, CV=3.1%) and modeled as lognormal distributions. Friction coefficient was modeled as uniform [0.15, 0.25] based on tribology literature. Monte Carlo propagation (N=5000) was used to compute the combined model input uncertainty contribution to each QoI."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test sample adequacy requires that the experimental sample set is representative of the simulated design and that sample-to-sample variability is characterized. Required level 3 demands N≥10 samples with documented dimensional inspection confirming conformance to nominal geometry.",
      "rationale": "Eleven non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw constructs were tested across two independent laboratories (Lab A: N=6, Lab B: N=5). All constructs were inspected dimensionally prior to testing; all critical dimensions (shank diameter, thread pitch, rod diameter, connector geometry) were within ±0.05 mm of nominal. Inter-laboratory variability in stiffness was 4.2% (CV), consistent with expected manufacturing variation. Sample traceability is documented in test records TR-LAB-A-2022-031 and TR-LAB-B-2022-018."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test condition adequacy requires that the experimental boundary conditions, loading rates, and environmental conditions are representative of the simulated scenario and that their influence on QoIs has been characterized. Required level 3 demands testing under at least two distinct condition sets to bound the QoI space.",
      "rationale": "Testing was conducted under a single set of ASTM F1717 standard conditions (room temperature, quasi-static loading rate of 5 mm/min, standard fixation block geometry). While the standard conditions are directly representative of the simulated scenario, no variation in loading rate or temperature was explored. This limits the achieved level to Gradation 2. The team acknowledges this gap and notes that the simulation is explicitly scoped to standard F1717 conditions; extrapolation to other loading rates or temperatures is not claimed."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Input parameter equivalency requires documented traceability between experimental measurements and simulation inputs, including uncertainty quantification of any parameter inferred rather than directly measured. Required level 3 demands that all influential simulation inputs are traceable to calibrated measurements with documented uncertainty.",
      "rationale": "All simulation inputs are traceable to calibrated measurement sources. Elastic modulus and yield strength are derived from tensile coupon tests performed on material certificates from the same lot as the test constructs. Geometry inputs are derived from CMM inspection reports. Friction coefficient is the only parameter not directly measured; its uncertainty is conservatively bounded by literature values and propagated through the uncertainty analysis. Traceability matrix TM-COU1-v2 documents the measurement source, calibration status, and uncertainty for each of the 14 influential input parameters."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Output comparison requires a quantitative metric that accounts for both simulation and experimental uncertainty. Required level 3 demands use of a validation metric that normalizes the model-experiment difference by the combined validation uncertainty (E/uval), with a pre-specified acceptance threshold.",
      "rationale": "The validation metric E/uval is computed for each QoI, where E is the signed difference between the FEA ensemble mean and the experimental mean, and uval is the combined uncertainty (simulation uncertainty from Monte Carlo propagation plus experimental uncertainty from inter-laboratory variability). Results: stiffness E/uval=0.82, yield force E/uval=1.14, force at 40 mm E/uval=0.97. All values are below the pre-specified threshold of 1.96 (95% confidence interval criterion). Additionally, the percentage difference criterion (<10%) is satisfied for all three QoIs (stiffness: 3.1%, yield force: 5.7%, force at 40 mm: 4.2%)."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "rationale": "The three quantities of interest — construct stiffness, yield force, and force at 40 mm displacement — are directly specified in ASTM F1717 as the primary mechanical performance endpoints for spinal implant constructs under compression-bending. These QoIs are mechanistically linked to the clinical failure modes of interest: construct loosening (stiffness), screw fatigue initiation (yield force), and gross construct failure (force at 40 mm). The selection of these QoIs was reviewed and endorsed by the clinical advisor team (memorandum COU1-CLINICAL-REVIEW-2022-09) and is consistent with FDA guidance on spinal implant testing (FDA 2015 Guidance on Testing Spinal Implants). The QoIs are computed directly from the FEA reaction force and displacement outputs without post-processing transformation, minimizing the risk of QoI derivation error. Sensitivity of the QoIs to all 14 model input parameters has been quantified, confirming that the QoIs are informative discriminators of model performance across the relevant input space. The relevance assessment satisfies Gradation 4 criteria: the QoIs are not only relevant to the COU but are the primary regulatory endpoints, and their clinical significance has been formally documented. No surrogate or proxy QoIs are employed. The direct correspondence between simulated and experimentally measured QoIs eliminates ambiguity in the comparison and ensures that the validation evidence is maximally informative with respect to the regulatory decision. This factor is assessed at the highest level warranted by the evidence; Gradation 5 was considered but not claimed because the QoI-to-clinical-outcome linkage, while strong, relies on epidemiological data from literature rather than device-specific post-market surveillance."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation activity relevance requires that the experimental validation scenario matches the COU in geometry, loading, boundary conditions, and material. Required level 3 demands that all primary scenario attributes are matched and any mismatches are explicitly documented and shown to have bounded influence on QoIs.",
      "rationale": "The validation experiments replicate the COU scenario in all primary attributes: identical non-cannulated 7.5 mm screw geometry, identical ASTM F1717 fixation block, identical quasi-static loading protocol, and identical Ti-6Al-4V material lot. The only identified mismatch is that the validation experiments use a fixed 35 mm pedicle screw insertion depth whereas the COU encompasses a range of 30–40 mm insertion depths. A targeted simulation study varying insertion depth across this range demonstrated less than 2% variation in all three QoIs, bounding the influence of this mismatch. This analysis is documented in sensitivity report SR-COU1-INSERTION-DEPTH-v1."
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/decision/nagaraja-cou1-decision-2026",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/synth/actor/fda-cdrh-osel-vv40-team",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "The credibility assessment for COU1 (non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw, ASTM F1717 compression-bending) is accepted at Medium assurance level. Twelve of thirteen V&V 40 credibility factors meet or exceed their required levels. The single shortfall (Test conditions, achieved level 2 vs. required level 3) is acknowledged and accepted on the basis that the simulation is explicitly scoped to standard ASTM F1717 conditions, the validation evidence directly supports this scope, and the regulatory decision does not require extrapolation beyond tested conditions. The validation metric E/uval is below 1.96 for all three QoIs, and the percentage difference criterion (<10%) is satisfied. The overall evidence package provides sufficient confidence to support the intended regulatory use of the FEA model.",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z"
  },
